^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Before getting into the bidding, let us discuss how to make 4@H. As the defense proceeded since diamonds broke 3-3, once cp ruffs a diamond, just need to draw trumps and dummy is good. Alternatively, clubs in north's hand are good. So could just draw 3 rounds of trumps and claim. This is a case where you need to count out your tricks. However, if you recall that at trick 4 had dorothy played @C2 instead of @S2 the contract would be set no matter what. They would get either a trick then or the @HJ in west hand would be promoted to a winner. However, kia played a high spade to encourage though earlier he showed holding two clubs.|
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the bidding. Cue bids are often good bids to make, and often less experienced players do not make enough use of them. First, the  1@S by kia was aggressive, even for my tastes. If his hand was KQJxx Jxx, xxx, xx then 1@S is quite good. My rule is, if I overcall a suit, I expect partner to lead it. If I have a good hand but bad suit, I will overcall, particularly at the one level, just to get a bid in. But with a weaker hand, I like to have a better suit. Now to the Western Cue bid.|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My 2@S bid is sometimes called a Western cue and asks cp to bid NT with a spade stopper. However, some people have a different meaning for western cue bid. Some people use "western cue" to mean what my 2@S bid meant. "pard bid NT with a spade stopper." However, the classical meaning of western cue is "I have half a stopper (such as Qxx), pard bid NT with half a stopper (such as Jxx)." Most people play Western cues the way I meant it, asking partner for full stopper. But the half stopper was how it was originally played.|
